## Program.cs — stdio transport with DI

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: stdio uses stdout for JSON-RPC, so all logs must go to stderr
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

builder.Services.AddHttpClient();  // registers IHttpClientFactory + HttpClient for DI

builder.Services.AddMcpServer()
    .WithStdioServerTransport()
    .WithToolsFromAssembly();      // discovers all [McpServerToolType] classes

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

## ApiTools.cs — tool class wrapping a REST API

```csharp
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Text.Json;

[McpServerToolType]
public class ApiTools(HttpClient httpClient, ILogger<ApiTools> logger)
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Fetch a user by their ID from the REST API.")]
    public async Task<string> GetUser(
        [Description("The numeric user ID")] int userId,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching user {UserId}", userId);
        var json = await httpClient.GetStringAsync(
            $"https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users/{userId}", cancellationToken);
        return json;
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("List all posts, optionally filtered by user ID.")]
    public async Task<string> ListPosts(
        [Description("Filter posts by this user ID (optional)")] int? userId = null,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var url = "https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts";
        if (userId.HasValue)
            url += $"?userId={userId.Value}";

        logger.LogInformation("Listing posts (userId filter: {UserId})", userId);
        return await httpClient.GetStringAsync(url, cancellationToken);
    }

    [McpServerTool(Destructive = false, ReadOnly = true),
     Description("Search posts by title keyword.")]
    public async Task<string> SearchPosts(
        [Description("Keyword to search for in post titles")] string keyword,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var json = await httpClient.GetStringAsync(
            "https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts", cancellationToken);
        var posts = JsonSerializer.Deserialize<JsonElement>(json);

        var matches = posts.EnumerateArray()
            .Where(p => p.GetProperty("title").GetString()!
                .Contains(keyword, StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase))
            .Select(p => p.ToString());

        return $"[{string.Join(",", matches)}]";
    }
}
```

## How DI works for MCP tools

The SDK has **two injection styles**:

**1. Constructor injection (non-static class, shown above)**
The class is instantiated per-request by the DI container. `HttpClient` and `ILogger<T>` are injected via the primary constructor. Register services in `Program.cs` (`AddHttpClient()`, etc.). `ILogger<T>` is registered by default.

**2. Method parameter injection (static class)**
DI services appear directly as method parameters:
```csharp
[McpServerToolType]
public static class StaticTools
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Ping a URL.")]
    public static async Task<string> Ping(
        [Description("URL to ping")] string url,
        HttpClient httpClient,              // injected by DI, hidden from schema
        CancellationToken cancellationToken) // also hidden from schema
    {
        var resp = await httpClient.GetAsync(url, cancellationToken);
        return $"Status: {(int)resp.StatusCode}";
    }
}
```

**Key rule:** `CancellationToken`, `IMcpServer`, `IProgress<T>`, and any DI-registered service are **automatically excluded** from the tool's JSON schema — only parameters with `[Description]` are exposed to the LLM.

### Scaffold it

```bash
dotnet new mcpserver -n MyApiServer
# Replace the generated files with the code above
dotnet build && dotnet run
```
